The Autobianchi Stellina is a small spider (a rear-engined cabrio) from the Italian automaker, Autobianchi (a subsidiary of the [MASK] group), built for only two years, 1964 and 1965.
Powered by [MASK] 600D's rear-mounted, water-cooled 767 cc straight-4 engine, delivering 29 hp (22 kW), the Stellina had drum brakes on all four wheels.
It was based on the mechanicals of the chassis [MASK] 600D, but had a unique unibody structure, with the outside panels made of fibreglass reinforced plastics, based on a steel frame.
Only 502 Stellinas were made until production ceased in 1965, when [MASK] launched a, slightly larger, similar Fiat 850 Spider.
